records.addlTxt:
Defendant Paul D Vinson in court with attorney Nathan Opland-Dobs.  Antonella Aleman appeared for the State of Wisconsin for Zachary Wittchow.

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements given by the state, defense, and the defendant.  

Court sentenced defendant to serve 120 DAYS in the House of Correction.  Court gives credit for 2 days served. 

Court STAYED sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for 18 MONTHS with the following conditions:

Court allows defendant  to be in the DOSAGE PROBATION PROGRAM, AND APPROVES EARLY TERMINATION IF COMPLETED.

- 30 DAYS, IMPOSED and STAYED, CONSECUTIVE in the House of Correction to be used by the agent for any violations.  Defendant shall serve 5 days for the first violation, 10 days for the second violation, and 15days for the third violation.

- AODA assessment and comply with any recommended treatment.
- Maintain absolute sobriety, no alcohol, no controlled substances without a valid prescription, with random drug tests and breathalyzers.  Defendant shall be tested twice per month.
- Enroll in a GED or HSED program.
- Seek and maintain full time employment, full time school, or a combination of both.
- Participate in any job training program as referred by agent.
- Complete a parenting course.
- No association with known drug users or dealers, and no contact at any place where illegal drugs are purchased, used, stored, packaged, or distributed.
- Complete 30 hours of community service.
- Court ordered defendant to provide a DNA, and pay all MANDATORY COURT costs, fees, surcharges, and assessments, while on probation.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means.  Cash bail to apply.  Defendant to make regular monthly payments.
- If defendant is arrested, and arises to probable cause, case will not be expunged.
- Any other conditions agent deemed appropriate.

Court allows for EXPUNGEMENT if defendant completes all conditions of probation.

Defendant Paul D Vinson in court with attorney Nathan Opland-Dobs.  Zachary A. Wittchow appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess any gun or other firearms. 
Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.  

Court also advises defendant if he is not a citizen of the United States of America, that upon a plea of guilty or no contest for this offense, he could be deported, excluded from admission to his country, or denied naturalization under federal law.  
Court advised that the defendant will have to provide a DNA sample, to the Wisconsin State Crime Laboratory for DNA testing.
